here we go. But I promise I'm not actually a depressing person. So climate change drives

00:00:06.560 --> 00:00:10.320
many different exposures that are linked across the continuum of cancer care.

00:00:10.900 --> 00:00:14.820
These include greater exposures to known carcinogens, influences on human behavior

00:00:14.820 --> 00:00:20.320
that similarly increase risk of cancer acquisition, as well as disruptions in cancer

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:25.760
treatments and additional issues into survivorship. This diagram gives us an overview of how

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:29.700
emissions lead to climate change and then how they interact with various cancers.

00:00:30.060 --> 00:00:35.780
So far, this has been best described for lung, skin, GI cancers, and the mechanisms for exposure

00:00:35.780 --> 00:00:43.320
include direct changes to the air, like increases in particulate matter exposure that lead to

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:47.740
higher incidence of lung cancer, changes in clothing worn during the spring months leading

00:00:47.740 --> 00:00:52.080
to increased UV exposure and higher rates of melanoma, decreased nutritional quality leading

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:53.940
to higher rates of GI cancers, et cetera.

00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:55.740
But.

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:00.140
But while a lot of exposure studies focus on cancer acquisition, there are recent examples

00:01:00.140 --> 00:01:05.500
relevant to oncology clinicians, such as this example showing how wildfire exposure for

00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:09.540
individuals who just underwent a curative lung cancer surgery is associated with higher rates

00:01:09.540 --> 00:01:14.500
of death, with the greatest risk associated with exposures in the first six months after surgery,

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:22.220
which is something potential. Oh, yeah, yeah, sorry. Sorry. So just this, this is one example

00:01:22.220 --> 00:01:25.580
connection that's been drawn that's relevant to oncology.

00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:29.800
Clinicians, which is essentially that patients who just went to underwent curative lung cancer

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:34.580
surgery and were exposed to wildfires within the first six months after the surgery had

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:40.680
higher risk of death. And you can kind of see the dose response here. But but the thing is that

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:45.980
outside of lung GI skin cancers, there's limited data. So we're wondering what might be clinically

00:01:45.980 --> 00:01:50.860
intervenable issue in the heme malignancies. And despite me not being a myeloma clinician,

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:55.400
we settled on myeloma because there is environmental health literature,

00:01:55.400 --> 00:02:00.720
that there's consistent associations between heat exposure and death that are mediated in the short

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:05.640
term by heat stroke and cardiovascular death and in the long term by renal dysfunction. And we all

00:02:05.640 --> 00:02:11.200
know that in myeloma, there's a variety of mechanisms through which myeloma impacts renal

00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:15.580
function and is also associated with increased mortality. So we really wanted to know if this

00:02:15.580 --> 00:02:20.340
heat exposure in patients with myeloma increased the risk of death. And if so, to what extent was

00:02:20.340 --> 00:02:25.220
that mediated by renal dysfunction? So we teamed up with some partners in the

00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:30.080
American Cancer Society and NASA who have access to the National Cancer Database, and then granular

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:35.000
longitudinal heat exposure data across the US to assess that question. And we looked at all patients

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:41.000
diagnosed from 2004 to 2022. And we use generally accepted definitions of heat exposure, looking to

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:46.440
see initially if there was a proxy signal for death by assessing peri diagnostic heat exposure,

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:55.040
so heat exposure in the first week after diagnosis. And then when patients have uncontrolled disease,

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:59.900
an AKI, and then we looked at the kind of the cumulative heat exposure across their whole disease

00:02:59.900 --> 00:03:07.260
course. So there were 335,000 patients in this analysis. And for the peri diagnostic kind of

00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:12.140
first look, about 1% of those had any heat exposure in the first week, and then a smaller

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:16.940
number had heat exposure kind of in the heatwave definition of four more days. And as you can see,

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:20.280
on the right, there's kind of this hint of a signal, which is just what we were looking for.

00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:24.860
Since this is just peri diagnostic exposure, we really surmise that this association was

00:03:24.860 --> 00:03:30.020
likely driven by exposure to additional heat throughout the treatment courses for the patients

00:03:30.020 --> 00:03:34.700
that had it in their first week. And you can see somewhat of a dose response here as you get to four,

00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:38.840
five, six, seven days with the hazard ratios going up, albeit modestly.

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:46.220
But this is kind of the main slide, essentially. Our main interest was really this cumulative

00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:50.600
exposure, which you can see here. And we used what is called a marginal structural model,

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:54.680
where you estimate the probability that each person actually had their observed

00:03:54.680 --> 00:03:59.420
exposure at the time point that they had it, and then weights individuals so their exposure becomes

00:03:59.420 --> 00:04:04.160
independent of confounders, meaning like, if two people were the same other than their heat

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:09.140
exposure history, how would their survival differ? This approach accounts for time-varying dynamic

00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:15.200
exposures like heat, confounders that impact prior exposure like renal dysfunction, as well

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:19.580
as things that we generally adjust for age, sex, race, comorbidities, hospital type,

00:04:19.580 --> 00:04:23.120
year of diagnosis, location, transplant in a time-varying way.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:29.660
The nice thing about this approach is that it's causal inference. And so instead of providing just

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:34.640
an association between heat exposure and survival, it allows us to kind of causally infer the degree

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:40.100
to which heat actually causes death. And so you can see here there was a dose response relationship

00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:44.300
where the more heat you're exposed to, the greater your likelihood of death. And I put

00:04:44.300 --> 00:04:49.880
up where U.S. cities fall on this in terms of the fraction of days per year that they have

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:54.320
with our definition of heat exposure. And you can see that for places like Boston, where I

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:59.840
am, it may not be such a big issue, but places like Houston, Phoenix, this is getting into

00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:05.480
territory where we think it really might matter. One thing that we did see was on the bottom left

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:11.240
that only about 22% of this increase in the hazard ratio was actually attributable to renal dysfunction,

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:17.720
which makes us think that there's probably other longer-term cardiovascular impacts that have been

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:24.140
coming out more recently as it relates to heat exposure in the general population. So we're

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:30.320
going back right now to do some more of those analyses. So what does this mean for us? Here are

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:35.060
some of the take-home messages for climate change studies in general that are relevant for people

00:05:35.060 --> 00:05:39.740
with cancer. And I've bolded the two that I've mentioned today. A lot of the worst effects of

00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:44.300
climate change are being borne out by those in the Global South and low-middle-income countries. But

00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:48.920
I think we also need to recognize that those with chronic illnesses like cancer and myeloma need to

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:52.520
be considered as very vulnerable to this and something that we should really think about

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:53.960
during our current practice. Thanks.

00:05:53.960 --> 00:05:54.840
Thank you.
